Event time vs Processing time
Event time: when event actually happened
Processing time: when Flink processed it
👉 Event time is more correct but harder

Watermark - A watermark is a signal that tells Flink “no more events before this timestamp are expected”, used to handle late/out-of-order events.
Why watermarks are needed?To handle:late events, out-of-order streams, event-time correctness
Core problem watermarks solve
👉 “When can I safely say no more events for this time window will arrive?”
Example:
window = 10:00–10:05
but events are still arriving late
Without watermark:
window never closes ❌
With watermark:
window closes when watermark passes end time ✔

Flink allows late data:You can configure:“I will still accept events 2 minutes late”
So:watermark passes window end but Flink still accepts late updates for a grace period
After that:data is dropped or sent to side output
Types of watermark strategies
1. Ascending watermark (ordered streams) - Assumes:events come in order, Fast and simple.
2. Bounded out-of-orderness watermark - Most common:allows events to be delayed by X time, Example:max delay = 5 seconds
3. Custom watermark generator - Used when:complex business logic, multiple event sources


Source and Sink - Source: where data comes from (Kafka, Kinesis) - Sink: where results go (DB, S3, Elasticsearch)
Out-of-order events handling - Flink uses: event time, watermarks to correctly place late events into correct windows.
State allows Flink to do: running counts, session tracking, aggregations, pattern detection. Without state → only stateless filtering.
Flink scales by: partitioning streams (keyBy), parallel operator execution, distributed cluster (TaskManagers).
Backpressure happens when: downstream operator is slower than upstream - causing upstream buffers to fill and slow down ingestion.
Fault tolerance in Flink uses: checkpointing, state snapshots, restart strategies
Checkpointing periodically saves: operator state , source offsets to durable storage for recovery.
Savepoint vs Checkpoint - Checkpoint: automatic, for recovery - Savepoint: manual, for upgrades/migration.
Flink reads Kafka offsets as part of checkpoint → ensures consistent replay after failure.
what happens on restart - Flink:restores last checkpoint, restores operator state, resets Kafka offsets, resumes processing
A distributed snapshot is a globally consistent state of:all operators, all streams, all offsets taken at the same logical time.
Trade-offs of large state - Large state leads to:high memory usage, slow checkpointing, longer recovery time, increased storage cost
External system consistency issue: Even if Flink is exactly-once internally: external DB writes may still duplicate unless idempotent or transactional sinks are used.
Why Flink is true streaming: Unlike Spark micro-batching:Flink processes event-by-event, maintains continuous state, low latency (ms-level)


