Skew + scaling problem
You have a Flink job: keyBy(userId), 1% of users generate 90% of traffic
👉 What happens in the system, and how would you fix it?
When keyBy(userId) has skewed distribution, a small number of tasks receive most of the events. These tasks become CPU and state bottlenecks,
causing uneven processing and backpressure while other tasks remain idle.
Internal effects:
         uneven load across TaskManagers
         large state for hot keys
         slower checkpointing for those operators
         pipeline throughput limited by slowest partition
Solutions - 
Key salting (correct idea, but must be precise) : Instead of modifying userId randomly: Add a controlled salt to split hot keys into sub-keys (e.g., userId + random bucket)
Then later:re-aggregate results
Two-stage aggregation (best practice) - Stage 1: userId + shardId → partial aggregates Stage 2: merge results per userId
Adaptive load balancing (advanced) - detect hot keys dynamically - redistribute partitions
Stateful optimization - reduce per-key state size , use TTL or windowing


A Flink job has:
         very large state (100s of GB)
         checkpoint duration keeps increasing
         occasional checkpoint failures
👉 What is happening internally and how would you fix it?
As Flink state grows, checkpointing becomes slower because Flink must serialize and snapshot a large amount of state (often from RocksDB or heap), 
upload it to durable storage (like S3), and wait for all operators to complete consistent snapshots.
This leads to:
         longer checkpoint duration
         network I/O bottlenecks (S3 upload)
         CPU overhead for serialization
         possible checkpoint timeout failures
Why checkpoints start failing
         state too large → checkpoint cannot finish within configured timeout
         backpressure delays checkpoint barriers
         slow task causes global checkpoint delay (straggler problem)
How to fix it (real Flink strategies)
✔ 1. Reduce state size (most important)
2. Incremental checkpoints (RocksDB) - RocksDB - only changes are checkpointed instead of full state snapshot
✔ 3. Optimize checkpoint interval (not just “make it smaller”) - too frequent → overhead - too infrequent → large recovery cost
👉 must tune based on throughput + state size
✔ 4. Use asynchronous + unaligned checkpoints - avoids waiting for slow operators - reduces barrier alignment bottleneck
✔ 5. Scale out state - increase parallelism , redistribute key space
